name: Eating with Industry
desc: This exclusive event will allow industry professionals to connect with some of The Ohio State University's best tech students over a networking dinner. The first half will be group-based speed networking which is similar to normal speed networking but with a few industry representatives paired with a small group of students. The following companies will be attending: Google, Target, CapitalOne, JP Morgan Chase, Northrup Grumman, Fast Enterprises, 84.51°, Upstart

name: Creative Jam presentations
desc:
In lieu of our regular Wednesday meeting, we will be attending the Adobe Creative Jam
The Adobe Creative Cloud team will host the Creative Jam presentations. This one-hour design showcase highlights the work of 3 local creative leaders. At the same time, in the next room, student design teams will be competing in the Creative Jam tournament, a 3-hour design charrette showdown. This event will have three categories: Graphic Design, Photography, Video Editing. Once the Creative Jam presentations wrap, tournament participants will take the stage to share their creations with you. As part of the audience, you’ll vote on each submission and select the People's Choice winner. There will also be Grand Prize winners decided by a group of Judges!

name: Paxata Tech Talk: ES2015 and the next generation of JS languages
desc: Now that the new spec for Javascript has been released it is time to catch up! During this presentation we will look at the changes to both the code and the ecosystem brought on by ES2015. We will explore how it will change frameworks like D3, Angular and React. Finally, we will explore how Paxata is working to upgrade from a legacy Angular 1 world to the promise of and Angular 2 one powered by Typescript.

name: Lean-In: Empowering Women in Technology

name: Tech Women Change the World - A Talk by Lauren Kinsey
desc: Lauren Kinsey is an expert on the intersection of gender and technology. A TEDx speaker and invited guest speaker at MIT, she has a talent for making her audiences feel engaged and motivated. She is the creator of womenintechsuccess.com and genderbalancechampion.com. Most recently, she designed a seven-step algorithm for gender balance, called SCALE UP.  Lauren claims tech companies using SCALE UP are guaranteed to achieve gender balance within five years of full implementation. Lauren has two main side projects she’s currently focused on. The first is working on a book about what cities can do to earn a reputation as a, “Top City for Women in Tech.” The second is blogging about information security at “Making Sense of Security.”
